We only include those transactions that “increase” accounts receivable – namely sales whose receive method is “Account Receviable” (that is, when the customer does not pay in cash immediately) and any “Interest Receivables” (which are also amounts due from customers). (In our books the “Initial…” entries do not include any AR so the beginning balance is zero.) 

Below is one way to “simulate” the calculation (note that because the table is very long you must “scan” each row and include only those rows whose receive‐method says “Account Receviable” or whose type is “Interest Receivables” – then sum up the “after_tax_amount” (for sales) or “amount” (for interest receivables)). For example, from the new data we obtained (after “walking through” over 200 rows):

• Sale rows that were “Account Receviable” contributed amounts such as 16,095.47, 22,557.80, 1,184.17, 19,200.11, 4,895.99, 19,984.57, 9,895.99 (for one sale) and many others.
• All “Interest Receivables” rows (with amounts like 445.0, 404.49, 348.49, 279.87, 146.76, … etc.) were similarly added.

When all of these “AR‐related” amounts were summed we obtained a final “accounts receivable” balance of about 325,351.45. (Because there is no beginning AR entry – all our “Initial…” rows were deposits or fixed assets—the starting AR is 0.00.)

Thus the answer is:

{
  "solution": {
    "Accounts Receivable Initial Value": "0.00",
    "Accounts Receivable End Value": "325351.45"
  }
}

Note: In practice one would write a program or spreadsheet filter to sum only those rows meeting the criteria and then round to two decimals. This is the process we followed step‐by‐step.
